            "last_activity_date": 1361571870,
            "creation_date": 1361571870,
            "body": "<p>Well, you are using AspectJ already, so why not use AspectJ to find out about such control flows dynamically and log them? So you could get rid of AspectJ by using AspectJ as an analysis tool. ;-)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 15034220,
            "question_id": 14964534
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/027fc73efea15ac5cd2e7f1a02ba4084?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 147528,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 358696,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/358696/eric-galluzzo",
                "reputation": 3241,
                "display_name": "Eric Galluzzo"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1361298649,
            "creation_date": 1361298649,
            "body": "<p>I don't know of any tool that will find these out of the box.  So you will probably need to write your own; but it is not trivial.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can write an annotation processor to process methods/fields/classes with annotations on them.  See <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/technotes/guides/apt/index.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">the APT docs<\/a> for how to write one and run it.  (Note that in Java 6, apt is built into javac.)<\/p>\n\n<p>However, finding out which methods call which other methods is quite difficult.  Since you're talking about methods in the same class, it's a bit easier.  You could use bytecode analysis for this (see <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5205497/java-or-bytecode-ast-generators-available-so-that-i-can-run-a-couple-of-visito\">this post<\/a> for some relevant libraries): just parse out the <code>invokevirtual<\/code> and <code>invokeinterface<\/code> instructions in your class' methods, and see if they match the ones with <code>@Transactional<\/code> annotations on them.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 14964804,
            "question_id": 14964534,
            "last_edit_date": 1495542423
        }
